#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:1
msgid "Correctness"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:3
msgid "Use checked or saturating arithmetic (`checked-arithmetic`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:5
msgid ""
"Use checked or saturating arithmetic for operations that could overflow. "
"Prefer explicit overflow handling over silent wrapping:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:11
msgid "// Good — overflow is handled explicitly\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:14
msgid "// Good — clamps instead of wrapping\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:17
msgid "// Bad — may silently wrap in release builds\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:22
msgid ""
"If wraparound behavior is intentional, use explicit `wrapping_*` or "
"`overflowing_*` operations and document why wrapping is correct."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:26
msgid "Use `debug_assert` for correctness-only checks (`debug-assert`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:28
msgid ""
"Assertions verifying invariants that should never fail in correct code "
"belong in `debug_assert!`, not `assert!`. `debug_assert!` is compiled out in "
"release builds, so the check catches bugs during development without costing "
"anything in production."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:40
msgid ""
"See also: [std::debug_assert!](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/macro."
"debug_assert.html) and [Rust Reference: `debug_assertions`](https://doc.rust-"
"lang.org/reference/conditional-compilation.html#debug_assertions)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:44
msgid "Propagate errors with `?` (`propagate-errors`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:46
msgid ""
"Use the `?` operator to propagate errors idiomatically. In kernel code, `."
"unwrap()` is rejected wherever failure is a legitimate possibility."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:53
msgid "// Good — propagate with ?\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:56
msgid "// Bad — unwrap hides the failure path\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-development/correctness.md:61
msgid ""
"See also: _The Rust Programming Language_, Chapter 9 \"Error Handling\" and "
"[Rust by Example: unpacking options and defaults with `?`](https://doc.rust-"
"lang.org/rust-by-example/std/result/question_mark.html)."
msgstr ""
